# Load whatever macros you need for the problem
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "PGchoicemacros.pl",
  "PGgraphmacros.pl",
  "freemanMacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

## Do NOT show partial correct answers
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 0;
TEXT(beginproblem());

$m=random(3,10,1);
$b=$m*$m+1;
$n=random(1,10,1);

BEGIN_TEXT
\{ textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "8.1","5") \}$BR
Calculate the arc length of \(y=$m x+1\) over the interval \([0,$n]\).
$PAR

\(s=\)\{ans_rule()\}
END_TEXT

$s=$n*sqrt($b);
ANS(num_cmp($s));

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$SOL

Since \(y=$m x+1\), we have \(y'=$m\), \(1+(y')^2=1+$m^2=$b\). Thus, 
the arc length \(S\) of \(y=$m x+1\) over the interval \([0,$n]\) is

\[
\begin{array}{lcl}
S& =& \int_0^{$n}\sqrt{1+(y')^2}dx\cr
&=&\int_0^{$n}\sqrt{$b} dx\cr
&=& \sqrt{$b} x|_0^{$n} \cr
& = & $n\sqrt{$b} = $s 
\end{array}
\]


END_SOLUTION
ENDDOCUMENT();
